"Li J., Wang M.-H., Ho Y.-S.","Trends in research on global climate change: A Science Citation Index Expanded-based analysis",2011,"Global and Planetary Change","77","1-2",,"13","20",,,10.1016/j.gloplacha.2011.02.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79956257394&partnerID=40&md5=06413ea77421215dc7d55697d302b193","Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Environmental Sciences and Engineering, Peking University, Beijing, 100871, China; Trend Research Centre, Asia University, Taichung 41354, Taiwan; Department of Environmental Sciences, Peking University, Key Laboratory of Water, Sediment Sciences, Ministry of Education, Beijing 100871, China","Li, J., Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Environmental Sciences and Engineering, Peking University, Beijing, 100871, China; Wang, M.-H., Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Environmental Sciences and Engineering, Peking University, Beijing, 100871, China; Ho, Y.-S., Trend Research Centre, Asia University, Taichung 41354, Taiwan, Department of Environmental Sciences, Peking University, Key Laboratory of Water, Sediment Sciences, Ministry of Education, Beijing 100871, China","This study was conceived to evaluate the global scientific output of climate change research over the past 18. years and to assess the characteristics of the research patterns, tendencies, and methods in the papers. Data were based on the online version of Science Citation Index Expanded from 1992 to 2009. Articles referring to climate change were assessed by distribution of source countries, source institutes, paper titles, author keywords, KeyWords Plus, abstracts, and the most cited articles in these years. By synthetic analysis of the four kinds of keywords, it was concluded that the items ""temperature"", ""environment"", ""precipitation"", ""greenhouse gas"", ""risk"", and ""biodiversity"" will be the foci of climate change research in the 21st century, while ""model"", ""monitoring"", and ""remote sensing"" will continue to be the leading research methods. A novel method, ""phylogeography"", may have a strong application potential in the near future. © 2011 Elsevier B.V.","Bibliometrics; Climate change; Model; Research trend; Word cluster analysis","Bibliometrics; Global climate changes; Novel methods; Online versions; Phylogeography; research methods; Research patterns; Research trend; Science citation index; Scientific output; Synthetic analysis; Word cluster analysis; Biodiversity; Cluster analysis; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Rating; Remote sensing; Research; Climate models; bibliography; climate change; climate modeling; cluster analysis; data set; global climate; greenhouse gas; phylogeography; remote sensing; research work; temporal analysis; trend analysis; twenty first century",,,,,,"Adam, D., The counting house (2002) Nature, 415, pp. 726-729; Augustin, L., Barbante, C., Barnes, P.R.F., Barnola, J.M., Bigler, M., Castellano, E., Cattani, O., Zucchelli, M., Eight glacial cycles from an Antarctic ice core (2004) Nature, 429, pp. 623-628; Avise, J.C., Arnold, J., Ball, R.M., Bermingham, E., Lamb, T., Neigel, J.E., Reeb, C.A., Saunders, N.C., Intraspecific phylogeography-the mitochondrial-DNA bridge between population-genetics and systematics (1987) Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst., 18, pp. 489-522; Baron, J., Thinking about global warming (2006) Clim. Change, 77, pp. 137-150; Biermann, F., 'Earth system governance' as a crosscutting theme of global change research (2007) Global Environ. Chang., 17, pp. 326-337; Bohringer, C., The Kyoto protocol: a review and perspectives (2003) Oxf. Rev. Econ. Policy, 19, pp. 451-466; Braun, T., Glanzel, W., Grupp, H., The scientometric weight of 50 nations in 27 science areas, 1989-1993. 1. All fields combined, mathematics, engineering, chemistry and physics (1995) Scientometrics, 33, pp. 263-293; Briones, M.J.I., Ineson, P., Piearce, T.G., Effects of climate change on soil fauna; responses of enchytraeids, diptera larva